226
00:17:53,760 --> 00:17:58,520
I have chosen the name collective because this part of the unconscious is not individual

227
00:17:58,520 --> 00:18:00,080
but universal.

228
00:18:00,080 --> 00:18:05,000
In contrast to the personal psyche, it has contents and modes of behavior that are more

229
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:09,240
or less the same everywhere and in all individuals.

230
00:18:09,240 --> 00:18:14,560
It is, in other words, identical in all men and thus constitutes the common psychic substrate

231
00:18:14,560 --> 00:18:20,760
of a super personal nature which is present in every one of us, end quote.

232
00:18:20,760 --> 00:18:27,240
The collective unconscious is often wrongly characterized as a sort of supernatural claim

233
00:18:27,240 --> 00:18:32,720
about humanity, as if we have some sort of psychic link between our minds or sort of

234
00:18:32,720 --> 00:18:36,160
hive mind unconsciousness, something of the like.

235
00:18:36,160 --> 00:18:43,000
The actual claim is simply that, in the same way that we're all born with certain instincts,

236
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:48,520
we're also all born with certain unconscious knowledge, that we have a pre-rational lexicon

237
00:18:48,520 --> 00:18:52,560
of imagery or symbolism that exists in all human minds.

238
00:18:52,560 --> 00:18:59,400
It's a starting, basic kit of information that's contained in the unconscious prior

239
00:18:59,400 --> 00:19:02,680
to any enculturation or upbringing.

240
00:19:02,680 --> 00:19:07,280
It's really no stronger of a claim than any claim about inborn traits or knowledge that

241
00:19:07,280 --> 00:19:11,680
exists in every human being, which I think would be fairly hard to argue against.

242
00:19:11,680 --> 00:19:17,400
To say that there is no universal, relatable palette of human emotions or impulses would

243
00:19:17,400 --> 00:19:19,600
simply be patently false.

244
00:19:19,600 --> 00:19:24,560
All human beings experience anger, experience sexual urges, experience hunger and thirst,

245
00:19:24,560 --> 00:19:29,520
all human beings have a fight or flight mechanism, we can easily accept such ideas.

246
00:19:29,520 --> 00:19:34,760
The troubling assertion that Jung makes, really, is that human nature also contains unconscious

247
00:19:34,760 --> 00:19:39,120
information, not just unconscious instinct.

248
00:19:39,120 --> 00:19:43,400
This is not to be considered knowledge or information of a kind that would necessarily

249
00:19:43,400 --> 00:19:49,760
be parsed by a rational discursive intellect, wherever it makes itself known, it appears

250
00:19:49,760 --> 00:19:58,640
not in the form of word concepts or abstract ideas, but in the form of these figures, images

251
00:19:58,640 --> 00:20:01,080
or narratives.

252
00:20:01,080 --> 00:20:07,080
We can see how Jung's work draws upon Freud, or serves as an elaboration upon it, and that

253
00:20:07,080 --> 00:20:13,760
Jung also believes that the repressed personal unconsciousness is what lies beneath the surface

254
00:20:13,760 --> 00:20:15,800
of the ego.

255
00:20:15,800 --> 00:20:22,280
But Jung thinks that this repressed, unacceptable psychic content is itself only another surface

256
00:20:22,280 --> 00:20:26,680
layer sitting upon this wide world of the id.

257
00:20:26,680 --> 00:20:33,640
Jung describes in this essay a number of profound religious dreams, in which this vaster unconsciousness

258
00:20:33,720 --> 00:20:37,960
is likened to a sea or a dark lake.

259
00:20:37,960 --> 00:20:43,000
The association of the unconsciousness with water is a common symbol found in such dreams

260
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:45,640
and experiences.

261
00:20:45,640 --> 00:20:51,760
Jung describes one dreamer who often saw the castle of the Grail sitting on a high mountaintop,

262
00:20:51,760 --> 00:20:57,960
but found that he could only reach it by passing, quote, a darksome gorge with underworldly

263
00:20:57,960 --> 00:21:01,680
water rushing along the bottom, end quote.

264
00:21:01,720 --> 00:21:06,280
Another patient, a Protestant theologian, had a recurring dream in which he was standing

265
00:21:06,280 --> 00:21:11,200
on a high mountain slope, looking down into the deep valley below, in which there was

266
00:21:11,200 --> 00:21:13,040
a dark lake.

267
00:21:13,040 --> 00:21:17,800
In the dream, he felt that something always held him back from going down to the lake,

268
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:20,480
but he decided to venture there anyway.

269
00:21:20,480 --> 00:21:26,440
As he approached the water, quote, everything grew dark and uncanny, and a gust of wind suddenly

270
00:21:26,440 --> 00:21:29,000
rushed over the face of the water.

271
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:35,200
He was seized by a panic fear and awoke, end quote.

272
00:21:35,200 --> 00:21:39,960
Water is only one of the common symbols for a confrontation with the unconsciousness,

273
00:21:39,960 --> 00:21:44,280
and a theme we can already see developing in these two example dreams is that in order

274
00:21:44,280 --> 00:21:50,920
to reach a place perceived as above the psyche, the ideal, the spiritual, however we may interpret

275
00:21:50,920 --> 00:21:54,680
it, one must first journey downward.

276
00:21:54,680 --> 00:22:00,360
The imagery of water, of a lake or sea seems natural for the human mind, it indicates something

277
00:22:00,360 --> 00:22:06,800
of which we can only see the surface, but beneath which there is an unfathomable depth.

278
00:22:06,800 --> 00:22:12,280
To approach the unconsciousness is always a somewhat fearful experience because the first

279
00:22:12,280 --> 00:22:18,080
layer of it contains those very repressed contents, of the contents that were repressed

280
00:22:18,080 --> 00:22:23,880
by the consciousness that characterized the Freudian version of the id, far from being

281
00:22:23,880 --> 00:22:30,600
strictly sexual, this unconscious layer represents everything about our public outward facing

282
00:22:30,600 --> 00:22:36,600
persona that we cannot show the world or manifest in our conscious life and thought.

283
00:22:36,600 --> 00:22:43,480
It is just as much our self as our waking self, but it's the dark reflection of that

284
00:22:43,480 --> 00:22:45,480
waking self.

285
00:22:45,480 --> 00:22:51,160
Jung writes, quote, whoever looks into the mirror of the water will see first of all

286
00:22:51,160 --> 00:22:58,880
his own face, whoever goes to himself risks a confrontation with himself, the mirror does

287
00:22:58,880 --> 00:23:04,440
not flatter, it faithfully shows whatever looks into it, namely the face we never show

288
00:23:04,440 --> 00:23:10,920
to the world because we cover it with the persona, the mask of an actor, but the mirror

289
00:23:10,920 --> 00:23:15,760
lies behind the mask and shows the true face, end quote.

290
00:23:15,760 --> 00:23:21,080
This is what Jung calls the shadow, it is the sum total of everything about ourselves

291
00:23:21,080 --> 00:23:25,640
which we have judged as negative, but it would be a mistake to think that the shadow does

292
00:23:25,640 --> 00:23:30,880
not operate in the world through our conscious personality, it does not remain confined to

293
00:23:30,880 --> 00:23:33,720
our unconscious thoughts or dreams.

294
00:23:33,720 --> 00:23:39,200
On the contrary, Jung says that quote, the shadow is a living part of the personality

295
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:44,160
and therefore wants to live with it in some form, it cannot be argued out of existence

296
00:23:44,160 --> 00:23:48,040
or rationalized into harmlessness, end quote.

297
00:23:48,040 --> 00:23:53,800
The way that Jung describes the shadow as a phenomenon, a psychic phenomenon is exceedingly

298
00:23:53,800 --> 00:23:59,360
fascinating because the shadow is both a terrible figure, but it is also the herald of a great

299
00:23:59,360 --> 00:24:01,840
personal transformation.

300
00:24:01,840 --> 00:24:07,000
Just as one must find their way across the terrible rushing waters of a dark gorge in

301
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:11,760
order to find their way to the holy grail, the shadow is the gateway to a deeper understanding

302
00:24:11,760 --> 00:24:13,680
of oneself.

303
00:24:13,680 --> 00:24:20,240
Jung writes in paragraph 45 of that same essay quote, the meeting with oneself is, at first,

304
00:24:20,240 --> 00:24:22,240
the meeting with one's own shadow.

305
00:24:22,240 --> 00:24:27,440
The shadow is a tight passage, a narrow door whose painful constriction no one has spared

306
00:24:27,440 --> 00:24:30,840
who goes down to the deep well, end quote.

307
00:24:30,840 --> 00:24:36,320
In order to understand how the shadow makes itself felt in our daily lives, it is essential

308
00:24:36,320 --> 00:24:40,720
that we understand Jung's concept of projection.

309
00:24:40,720 --> 00:24:46,400
Consciousness naturally raises certain aspects of the self into a state of conscious sovereignty,

310
00:24:46,400 --> 00:24:51,760
and so long as the conscious persona is healthy, functioning, flourishing, those unconscious

311
00:24:51,760 --> 00:24:57,720
contents which are unacceptable for the social life are deprived of energy, so to speak,

312
00:24:57,720 --> 00:24:59,840
they're kept subordinated.

313
00:24:59,840 --> 00:25:04,480
But if the conscious domain of the psyche becomes unbalanced, unhealthy in some way,

314
00:25:04,480 --> 00:25:10,040
is challenged or disturbed in some serious way, those unconscious complexes will start

315
00:25:10,040 --> 00:25:15,360
to take charge of it, and furthermore the unconscious contents are experienced as something

316
00:25:15,360 --> 00:25:18,120
foreign to the conscious self.

317
00:25:18,120 --> 00:25:25,560
Jung writes quote, the collective unconscious is anything but an encapsulated personal system.

318
00:25:25,560 --> 00:25:31,280
It is sheer objectivity, as wide as the world and open to all the world.

319
00:25:31,280 --> 00:25:36,160
There I am the object of every subject, in complete reversal of my ordinary consciousness

320
00:25:36,160 --> 00:25:41,520
where I am always the subject that has an object, end quote.

321
00:25:41,520 --> 00:25:47,760
And so, when someone's unacceptable unconscious content that Jung calls their shadow begins

322
00:25:47,760 --> 00:25:52,720
to make itself forceful over the conscious personality, it is natural that we should

323
00:25:52,720 --> 00:25:57,720
experience this as something external, that we should therefore project that feeling,

324
00:25:57,720 --> 00:26:02,200
that complex, that type, onto the external world.

325
00:26:02,200 --> 00:26:06,680
Jung clarifies in one section that this term projection should not be taken to mean that

326
00:26:06,680 --> 00:26:11,520
the psyche has actually reached out into the objective world and exercised a power over

327
00:26:11,520 --> 00:26:13,000
the external.

328
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:17,960
He says another term one could use for projection would be introjection, the use of external

329
00:26:17,960 --> 00:26:24,280
objects or entities to symbolize some process which is actually internal to the subject,

330
00:26:24,280 --> 00:26:28,640
that really we're not so much pitching the psyche out with projection so much as we are

331
00:26:28,640 --> 00:26:31,040
bringing the external in.

332
00:26:31,040 --> 00:26:36,640
So for an example of the shadow crashing into the psyche of an otherwise healthy mind,

333
00:26:36,640 --> 00:26:41,720
suppose we have an individual who feels that aggressiveness and competition, whether it

334
00:26:41,720 --> 00:26:47,040
be sports or one's career or simply social life in general, that it's inappropriate

335
00:26:47,040 --> 00:26:53,320
and it's mean spirited, that one should not ever express hostility towards one's fellow

336
00:26:53,320 --> 00:26:58,960
competitors, you should comport yourself with a kind of mutual respect.

337
00:26:58,960 --> 00:27:03,720
You would probably all say these are admirable values for one to hold, but perhaps we can

338
00:27:03,720 --> 00:27:09,160
imagine someone who feels this value of a desire for mutual respect and competition

339
00:27:09,160 --> 00:27:15,240
so strongly that he always suspects that his competitors are hostile toward him.

340
00:27:15,240 --> 00:27:19,600
When he loses on the football field, he assumes his opponents must be putting his team down

341
00:27:19,600 --> 00:27:22,320
in their own locker room after the game.

342
00:27:22,320 --> 00:27:27,160
When a coworker passes him and gets the promotion, he assumes that this person secretly hates

343
00:27:27,280 --> 00:27:29,280
him or looks down upon him.

344
00:27:29,280 --> 00:27:34,400
And accordingly, because all of our sportsmanship is just a false veneer in the first place,

345
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:39,200
perhaps he ends up feeling that hostility towards all of his competitors around him.

346
00:27:39,200 --> 00:27:43,240
This fills him with a sense of guilt, but he reminds himself that it's really the fault

347
00:27:43,240 --> 00:27:47,160
of all of those around him who have disrespected him over the years.

348
00:27:47,160 --> 00:27:51,480
A Jungian might look at such a person and see that he's become possessed by his shadow

349
00:27:51,480 --> 00:27:53,400
to some extent.

350
00:27:53,400 --> 00:27:57,960
And in this process, he is experienced as something foreign, something alien to his

351
00:27:57,960 --> 00:27:59,640
ego consciousness.

352
00:27:59,640 --> 00:28:04,880
With all of his moral pretensions, that mutual respect is the basis of all friendly competition,

353
00:28:04,880 --> 00:28:09,960
but he always projects his own shadow onto the behaviors of his friends and his coworkers.

354
00:28:09,960 --> 00:28:14,880
The fact that it is really he who feels this deep hostility and disrespect towards others

355
00:28:14,880 --> 00:28:19,800
is masked by this projection and it becomes a way for him to deal with the guilt that

356
00:28:19,800 --> 00:28:22,800
he feels for feeling that way.

357
00:28:22,800 --> 00:28:26,880
All of this would be in the patient's shadow self.

358
00:28:26,880 --> 00:28:30,960
Jung gives an explanation in broad, somewhat poetic terms of what the person possessed

359
00:28:30,960 --> 00:28:36,280
by the shadow or by their quote, inferior functions is like.

360
00:28:36,280 --> 00:28:42,920
This is in concerning rebirth paragraph 222 of archetypes and the collective unconscious

361
00:28:42,920 --> 00:28:44,720
quote.

362
00:28:44,720 --> 00:28:50,680
The inferior function is practically identical with the dark side of the human personality,

363
00:28:50,680 --> 00:28:55,280
the darkness which clings to every personality is the door into the unconscious and the gateway

364
00:28:55,280 --> 00:29:01,160
of our dreams, from which those two twilight figures, the shadow and the anima, step into

365
00:29:01,160 --> 00:29:07,440
our nightly visions, or remaining invisible take possession of our ego consciousness.

366
00:29:07,440 --> 00:29:12,240
A man who is possessed by his shadow is always standing in his own light and falling into

367
00:29:12,240 --> 00:29:14,320
his own traps.

368
00:29:14,320 --> 00:29:18,960
Whenever possible, he prefers to make an unfavorable impression on others.

369
00:29:18,960 --> 00:29:23,840
In the long run, luck is always against him because he is living below his own level,

370
00:29:23,840 --> 00:29:28,080
and at best only attains what does not suit him.

371
00:29:28,080 --> 00:29:33,240
And if there is no doorstep for him to stumble over, he manufactures one for himself and then

372
00:29:33,240 --> 00:29:38,600
fondly believes he has done something useful.

373
00:29:38,600 --> 00:29:42,280
Jung mentions the anima there, which we will address in a little bit, but the main thing

374
00:29:42,280 --> 00:29:48,240
to remember about the shadow, it's the unacceptable side of ourselves, which nevertheless exists

375
00:29:48,440 --> 00:29:52,920
and sometimes motivates our actions and that we therefore project onto the external in order

376
00:29:52,920 --> 00:29:56,280
to deal with the cognitive dissonance that that brings.

377
00:29:56,280 --> 00:30:00,520
We would sooner see the contents of our own shadow in our friends, in our neighbors, in

378
00:30:00,520 --> 00:30:06,040
our interlocutors than in ourselves, and such a person who is possessed by their shadow

379
00:30:06,040 --> 00:30:11,800
will consequently bring forth the very aspect of himself that he despises and then experience

380
00:30:11,800 --> 00:30:13,800
it as something alien.

381
00:30:13,800 --> 00:30:18,920
We will get in our own way and then perceive that obstacle as the other.

382
00:30:18,920 --> 00:30:24,040
In dreams, the shadow can appear as numerous images, sometimes as a hostile animal or a

383
00:30:24,040 --> 00:30:28,120
predator, sometimes as a primitive human being.

384
00:30:28,120 --> 00:30:33,520
The shadow appears throughout the mythology of mankind as an adversary or as a dark inversion

385
00:30:33,520 --> 00:30:35,640
of the heroic figure.

386
00:30:35,640 --> 00:30:40,720
Because the origin of these unacceptable drives or impulses is within our animal nature, the

387
00:30:40,720 --> 00:30:47,320
association of the shadow with less conscious animals or more instinctive forms of life

388
00:30:47,320 --> 00:30:50,000
seems somewhat obvious.

389
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:56,840
But in many cultures, Jung argues, the shadow appears in the mythology as a trickster figure.

390
00:30:56,840 --> 00:31:01,920
Such a figure is something of a riddle because the trickster entities of many religions and

391
00:31:01,920 --> 00:31:07,800
superstitious traditions is a sort of mixed and paradoxical character.

392
00:31:07,800 --> 00:31:11,720
Jung says that there is something of the trickster in the image of the shaman and the medicine

393
00:31:11,720 --> 00:31:17,320
man, the wild figure who lives at the boundaries of society but has a connection with the world

394
00:31:17,320 --> 00:31:18,960
of spirits.

395
00:31:18,960 --> 00:31:24,720
The poltergeist is another such example within popular folklore, in this case of a trickster

396
00:31:24,720 --> 00:31:26,200
spirit.

397
00:31:26,200 --> 00:31:31,280
Jung also brings up the contradictoryness of the trickster in European folklore in the

398
00:31:31,280 --> 00:31:37,200
form of the devil, regarded as the ape of God, who is sometimes portrayed in the legends

399
00:31:37,200 --> 00:31:43,440
as a simpleton who is easily fooled or cheated by ordinary human beings.

400
00:31:43,440 --> 00:31:48,560
There are also the figures out of folktales such as Tom Thumb or Stupid Hans and one

401
00:31:48,560 --> 00:31:54,440
of Grimm's fairy tales, the spirit Mercurius, who takes his name from the Greek god Mercury,

402
00:31:54,440 --> 00:31:57,800
is outwitted by a simple peasant.

403
00:31:57,800 --> 00:32:03,240
Jung argues in his essay Psychology of the Trickster Figure that quote, if the myth were

404
00:32:03,240 --> 00:32:08,680
nothing but an historical remnant, one would have to ask why it has not long since vanished

405
00:32:08,680 --> 00:32:13,320
into the great rubbish heap of the past.

406
00:32:13,320 --> 00:32:19,160
Instead, the trickster still fascinates us, whether it's Mephisto and Goethe's Faust,

407
00:32:19,160 --> 00:32:25,760
Loki and the Norse myths, or for that matter, Loki in the latest Marvel production, or in

408
00:32:25,760 --> 00:32:31,760
the horror stories of poltergeists and other such mischievous spirits.

409
00:32:31,800 --> 00:32:37,000
Jung references the strange European tradition of celebrating the trickster.

410
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:41,560
Jung believes that these fests and carnivals were in some sense rooted in the Roman holiday

411
00:32:41,560 --> 00:32:47,960
of Saturnalia, in which societal roles were reversed, slaves ordered around their masters,

412
00:32:47,960 --> 00:32:48,960
and so on.

413
00:32:48,960 --> 00:32:54,760
In medieval Europe, the New Year was celebrated with singing and dancing, called the Fool's

414
00:32:54,760 --> 00:32:55,760
Feast.

415
00:32:55,760 --> 00:33:02,520
In the year 1198, apparently the festivities got so out of hand that Pope Innocent III

416
00:33:02,520 --> 00:33:09,360
railed against the, quote, gests and madness that make the clergy a mockery, end quote,

417
00:33:09,360 --> 00:33:13,840
and the, quote, shameless frenzy of their play acting, end quote.

418
00:33:13,840 --> 00:33:19,280
And even 200 years later, a letter to the theological faculty of Paris complained that

419
00:33:19,280 --> 00:33:25,520
even the clergy was getting involved with these Fool's Feasts and that they were farcically

420
00:33:25,520 --> 00:33:29,520
electing a Fool's Pope during these festivities.

421
00:33:29,520 --> 00:33:35,000
There was also the Festum Assenorum, the Ass Festival, or Donkey Festival.

422
00:33:35,000 --> 00:33:39,520
As Jung mentions, this is referenced by Nietzsche himself and thus spoke Zarathustra, the chapter

423
00:33:39,520 --> 00:33:46,520
named the Ass Festival, and in Jung's estimation that chapter of Zarathustra is, quote, a deliberately

424
00:33:46,520 --> 00:33:50,840
blasphemous parody of the mass, end quote.

425
00:33:50,840 --> 00:33:56,240
As Jung explains, we cannot source this apparently farcical celebration to Nietzsche himself.

426
00:33:56,240 --> 00:34:02,080
These strange ecclesiastical customs are the organic products of the Middle Ages.

427
00:34:02,080 --> 00:34:07,920
A procession of men marched with a donkey, decked with a golden canopy, and they marched

428
00:34:07,920 --> 00:34:12,600
all the way into the church, and there the priest would conclude mass by braying three

429
00:34:12,600 --> 00:34:18,600
times, like a donkey, and the priests and archbishops then played a ballgame inside

430
00:34:18,600 --> 00:34:20,600
the church.

431
00:34:20,600 --> 00:34:25,860
Jung writes, quote, in picker-esque tales and carnivals and revels, and magic rites of

432
00:34:25,860 --> 00:34:31,320
healing and man's religious fears and exaltations, the phantom of the trickster haunts the mythology

433
00:34:31,320 --> 00:34:38,560
of all ages, sometimes in quite unmistakable form, sometimes in strangely modified guise,

434
00:34:38,560 --> 00:34:44,120
end quote, and a bit further in the essay Jung continues, quote, the trickster motif

435
00:34:44,120 --> 00:34:49,760
does not crop up only in its mythical form, but appears just as naively and authentically

436
00:34:49,760 --> 00:34:52,400
in the unsuspecting modern man.

437
00:34:52,400 --> 00:34:58,120
Whenever in fact he feels himself at the mercy of annoying, quote, accidents, which thwart

438
00:34:58,120 --> 00:35:04,400
his will and his actions with apparently malicious intent, he then speaks of, quote, hoodos

439
00:35:04,400 --> 00:35:09,200
and jinxes, or of the mischievousness of the object.

440
00:35:09,200 --> 00:35:14,320
Here the trickster is represented by counter tendencies in the unconscious, and in certain

441
00:35:14,320 --> 00:35:20,640
cases by a sort of second personality of a purile and inferior character, not unlike

442
00:35:20,640 --> 00:35:26,120
the personalities who announce themselves at spiritualistic sciences, and cause all those

443
00:35:26,120 --> 00:35:30,520
ineffably childish phenomena so typical of poltergeists.

444
00:35:30,520 --> 00:35:34,720
I have, I think, found a suitable designation for this character component when I called

445
00:35:34,720 --> 00:35:36,640
it the shadow.

446
00:35:36,640 --> 00:35:42,720
On the civilized level, it is regarded as a personal gaffe, slip, faux pas, etc., which

